title: $A backs away from two week high
text:
Wed, Aug 5, 2015, 5:52 PM AEST - Australia Markets closed $A backs away from two week high AAP â€“ 13 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar has eased after a rally fuelled by the Reserve Bank's latest comments that pushed it past 74 US cents. 
At 1700 AEST on Wednesday, the currency was trading at 73.49 US cents, down from 73.77 cents on Tuesday. 
In the early hours of Wednesday morning the currency peaked at 74.30 US cents, its highest level since July 22. 
The RBA on Tuesday said the Aussie dollar is "adjusting to the significant declines in key commodity prices", a change from its previous comments that it needed to fall further. 
The currency market was "completely wrongfooted" by the RBA's change of tune, OANDA Australia and Asia Pacific senior trader Stephen Innes said. 
However the currency lost ground on expectations the US Federal Reserve will soon make its first interest rate hike since before the global financial crisis. 
Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta president Dennis Lockhart, who is a voting member on the Fed's policy making committee, said it would take a significant deterioration in the economy to convince him not to lift US interest rates in September. 
"I suspect the reason the Aussie did not move aggressively to the downside on his comments is the fact traders are waiting for Friday's US jobs data before stamping the September Fed rate hike ticket," Mr Innes said. 
"In the meantime, we still have tomorrow's Aussie employment data to contend with, so there could be more fireworks in store." 
CURRENCY SNAPSHOT AT 1700 AEST ON WEDNESDAY 
One Australian dollar buys: 
* 73.49 US cents, from 73.77 cents on Tuesday 
* 91.41 Japanese yen, from 91.46 yen 
* 67.59 euro cents, from 67.32 euro cents 
* 112.59 New Zealand cents, from 111.93 NZ cents 
* 47.23 British pence, from 47.28 pence 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
